# 2. 昼下がりの刺繍教室

Mafuyu: Alright, Hinomori, I'm ready to learn.
Shizuku: Okay, I'm ready as well.
Shizuku: Today, I'll be teaching you some simple sewing techniques. We'll try a few designs once you've gotten the hang of them.
Mafuyu: Sewing techniques? As in the stitches you mentioned?
Shizuku: Yes, in home ec, you likely learned them as “nami-nui” and “hongaeshi-nui”, which translate into “running stitches” and “back stitches” in English.
Mafuyu: I see. You're so knowledgeable... Like a real teacher.
Shizuku: Oh, you think so...?
Shizuku: Let's see... Then, why don't we begin by trying some outline stitches.
Shizuku: You use them quite a lot to draw lines and fill in gaps. First, let me show you.
Mafuyu: Okay, thank you.
Shizuku: Once you have your thread knot and poke the needle back out, you'll stick it back in a short distance away...
Shizuku: Next, you go back about half a step and stick the needle in at the midpoint of your previous stitch. By doing this a few times...
Mafuyu: Oh, it's turning into a line.
Shizuku: Yes, this is how you do an outline stitch. Compared to a back stitch, the line you create ends up being a little thicker.
Shizuku: Next, let's try doing it together,
Mafuyu: Okay. So, start by making a thread knot and...
Mafuyu: How does this look?
Shizuku: Yes, that's excellent! Your line is very straight.
Shizuku: You could try spacing your stitches more evenly to make it look cleaner, but that's just me splitting hairs.
Mafuyu: Ah, thank you. I'll give that a try.
Female Students: Hey, have you decided what you're gonna do for Valentine's Day yet?
Female Students: I have, but I'm keeping my present a secret until the day of.
Female Students: Aww... I wanted to use your idea as a springboard.
Shizuku: Oh...
Mafuyu: The girls in the corridor seem to be having a fun conversation.
Shizuku: They're already getting ready for Valentine's Day.
Mafuyu: I'll need to start thinking about that soon.
Shizuku: Do you plan on giving a gift to someone?
Mafuyu: Yes, my groupmates are going to throw a Valentine's Day party, and they told me to bring something.
Shizuku: Oh, with Ena and the others? That sounds like fun.
Shizuku: I also plan on giving gifts on Valentine's Day to those around me.
Shizuku: It's a wonderful opportunity for me to show my appreciation for them.
Shizuku: They mean so much to me, so I want my gifts to them to reflect that fact.
Mafuyu: Gifts that mean something. I like the sound of that.
Mafuyu: But what would count as that?
Shizuku: Well... Oh, I know! You could give them accessories that you embroidered yourself.
Mafuyu: Embroidery, huh... Yes, a gift does tend to feel more special when you know it's handmade.
Shizuku: Right? This is just how I feel, but I believe quite a lot of emotion goes into every stitch.
Mafuyu: A lot of emotion...?
Shizuku: Yes. The process of choosing the right design for the person you have in mind, and carefully stitching it in, really allows you to channel in your emotions.
Shizuku: Which is why, for those truly special occasions, I almost always give people things that I embroidered myself.
Mafuyu: I see. It's a wonderful reflection of who you are, Hinomori.
Mafuyu: So, let's do our best to make gifts that our respective recipients will really enjoy.
Shizuku: Yes, let's!
Haruka: Oh, Shizuku, there you are.
Shizuku: Haruka?
Haruka: Oh, Asahina, hello. I didn't realize you were with her.
Mafuyu: Hello. Are you here for Hinomori?
Haruka: Yes, I need to steal her for a minute.
Haruka: Did you see the message in our group chat, Shizuku?
Shizuku: What message? Give me just a second...
Shizuku: Oh no...! I'm so sorry! My phone's battery ran out...!
Haruka: Hehe. I had a feeling. Anyway, please take a look at it when you get a chance. It details our activities for the near term.
Shizuku: Okay. Thank you for taking the time to come to tell me, Haruka!
Haruka: You're welcome. Also, what were you two doing just now?
Shizuku: Embroidery practice.
Mafuyu: Hinomori agreed to teach me how to embroider after I told her that we were assigned a project for home ec.
Shizuku: We were just working on some basic stitches, but we'll be putting them into practice in a little bit.
Shizuku: For example, by making these flowers.
Haruka: Wow, they're beautiful... You can embroider these yourself?
Shizuku: Yes, these sorts of designs are perfect for accenting handkerchiefs and socks. I actually embroider these quite a lot.
Haruka: Really? Putting in your own designs like that does sound like fun.
Haruka: This might be worth streaming...
Shizuku: Wait, like an embroidery stream?
Haruka: Yeah. Remember how Airi streamed a cooking lesson the other day?
Haruka: That got a lot of positive feedback, because it's such a useful life skill. I have a feeling that a lot of people would be interested in you teaching them how to embroider too.
Shizuku: Yes, I see your point! The segments that allow our viewers to follow along and participate have been very popular...
Haruka: Oh, I'm sorry... I didn't mean to turn this into work talk.
Mafuyu: No, that's okay. I can tell that you both care very deeply about your fans.
Mafuyu: I also think that's a good idea for a stream. I mean, Hinomori, you're such an incredible teacher.
Shizuku: You think so? It's very encouraging to hear you say that, Asahina.
Haruka: Then, let's ask Airi about this.
Haruka: Oh, also... Would it be possible for you to teach me how to embroider sometime too? That should help us put the plan for our stream together.
Shizuku: Of course. I'll make sure to set aside some time for that.
Haruka: Okay, thanks.
Mafuyu: In that case, Kiritani, why don't you join us now?
Haruka: Huh? But...
Mafuyu: Don't worry, we've only just begun. Oh, unless you have a prior engagement...
Shizuku: What a good idea! What do you say, Haruka?
Haruka: Then, if you don't mind me jumping in...
Mafuyu: Yes, let's practice together.
Shizuku: Then, Haruka, I'll also start teaching you some basic stitches.
Haruka: Thank you, Ms. Shizuku.
Shizuku: Of course♪
Haruka: Shizuku, can you take a look at my lazy daisy stitch? Did I get it right?
Shizuku: Yes! Your spacing is perfect, and you also made sure not to pull too hard as you sewed. Next, let's...
Shizuku: Oh, lunch is about to end...
Mafuyu: You're right. We were so focused that the time just flew by.
Haruka: Thank you for teaching us all this, Shizuku.
Haruka: I know we only got to practice doing a couple stitches today, but seeing my work slowly come together was really fun.
Mafuyu: Yes, I know what you mean. It's always nice to see the effort you put in bear fruit like this.
Shizuku: Hehe. I'm glad you both had so much fun.
Shizuku: To be honest, I was hoping to get you two to embroider some flowers...
Haruka: Yeah, that would be fun to do during our stream.
Mafuyu: Then, since we couldn't quite finish today, why don't we meet again sometime?
Shizuku: Yes, let's do that!
Shizuku: Oh, I know...! Why don't you try embroidering some penguins, Haruka?
Haruka: Wait, you can embroider penguins?
Shizuku: Yes. I have a book of animal patterns at home, so I'll bring it with me next time.
Haruka: Thanks...!
Mafuyu: Hehe. I'll be looking forward to our next embroidery lesson. When should we meet next?
Shizuku: Well... We could meet again in one of the classrooms during lunch...
Shizuku: Or this other place I really recommend. Would you both be okay with that?
